commitResults.messageBody:
Added the following functionalities to the main() function:
* Logo & introduction to app
* Echo/print out user input
* Exit app when user types "bye"

New features:
*App now keeps track of items entered by user, up to a number of 100 items
*App can list items entered by user if they type 'list'

Edited:
*Starting instructions to describe new features

- Added in Task class, to help keep track of items as tasks and mark them as 'done'
- Added in new instructions related to marking tasks as 'done'

Added in different task subclasses, making the task list more customisable and versatile
-ToDo tasks are similar to tasks in the previous level, just a description
-Deadline tasks will have an additional deadline time parameter, represented as a String for now
-Event tasks have a time range parameter, also represented as a String for now

Added in a help command to guide the user on valid commands.
Added in some sample inputs and outputs to input.txt and EXPECTED.txt respectively to semi-automate the testing of the Duke Bot.

Added various error handling to ensure the bot runs smoothly without breaking, these include checking for:
-Invalid/Out-of-bounds integers when marking tasks as done
-Unrecognised commands when the bot is idle
-Not having a description for tasks

Added the feature to delete tasks from the task list.
This would be useful when the user completes a task and/or wants to make a new list of tasks
-The task list has been changed to an ArrayList type instead of a basic array.
-The limit of 100 tasks is still maintained to prevent the list from being too long.

Added ability for bot to save task list to a file every time the task list is updated
-The file is hardcoded to "./duke.txt"

Added ability for bot to recognise dates and times
-Program now properly formats string inputs for dates and times
-Deadline and Event tasks now take in LocalDate and LocalTime parameters

Enhanced the OOP of the bot, improving code maintainability and quality
-Code is now modelled into 4 classes: Ui, Parser, TaskList and Storage

Added ability to load tasks from Duke.txt which was missing in Level-7

-Put all classes into one complete package "duke"

-Minor bug fixes for Ui prompts

-Created a JUnit class DukeTest with several tests to test various methods
These include Task creation, Storage.load() and TaskList.getTask()

-Updated .gitignore to ignore some extra files

Added JavaDoc documentation to elaborate on Duke classes and methods

Updated .gitignore to ignore Duke.txt

Improved code readability by following Java Coding Standard
-Fixed indentation of switch case blocks
-Added spaces between parameters and commas for functions
-Fixed text wrapping issues
Added the ability for the bot to search for specific tasks based on keywords in their descriptions
-Based on given Java Code Standard
Grouped classes into separate packages to improve code readability and maintainability

Converted the text UI to a graphical UI to make the bot more user friendly and appealing
-Added JavaFX libraries
-Created java and fxml files for Dialogs and Window
-Refactored some code in Parser.java

Deleted Text Ui (Ui.java) and files from A-TextUiTesting as they are no longer necessary

Currently the code for the bot across multiple classes is not entirely refined and is a bit messy.

The code is improved based on the code quality topics learnt in CS2103T so as to make it more readable and maintainable.

This includes separating parts of long methods out, adding more javadoc comments, and minor bug fixes and optimisations.
Used assert to confirm if TaskList is not empty

commitResults.messageTitle: Implement C-Sort extension for individual project
commitResults.messageBody:
Right now, there is no way to manipulate the task list
besides adding and deleting a task.

This can make the task list messy and difficult to track tasks
after multiple insertions or deletions.

A sort function is implemented which allows the user
to sort the task list by task and date/time.

This allows them to separate out different types of tasks,
and see which deadlines/events are coming up soon.
